$project14 = Project::create(['name' => ' Day of the Week','open_date' => '2018-07-14 0:00:00','close_date' => '2018-07-16 0:00:00','prompt' => '\n<div>See the project instructions at <a href="http://www2.cose.isu.edu/~edwajohn/teaching/cs1181-3/project-day-of-week.pdf" target="_blank">this link</a>.</div>\n','pre_code' => '','start_code' => '','solution' => '# Prompt the user and get the day, month and year\nday = 3#input("Please enter the day: ")\nmonth = 12#input("Please enter the month (January = 1, February = 2, etc): ")\nyear = 1974#input("Please enter the year: ")\n# Compute the day of the week using Gauss" algorithm,\n# as described on Wikipedia\nd = day\nm = 1 + ((month+9) % 12)\ny = year\nif month == 1 or month == 2:\n    y = year - 1;\nw = (d + (int)(2.6*m - 0.2) + 5 * (y % 4) + 4 * (y % 100) + 6 * (y % 400)) % 7\nprint("d = {}\nm = {}\ny = {}".format(d, m, y))\n# Output result by doing if/else on the variable w\nif w == 0:\n    dayOfWeek = "Sunday"\nelif w == 1:\n    dayOfWeek = "Monday"\nelif w == 2:\n    dayOfWeek = "Tuesday"\nelif w == 3:\n    dayOfWeek = "Wednesday"\nelif w == 4:\n    dayOfWeek = "Thursday"\nelif w == 5:\n    dayOfWeek = "Friday"\nelif w == 6:\n    dayOfWeek = "Saturday"\nprint("The day of the week is {}.".format(dayOfWeek))\n','module_id' => $module12->id,'previous_lesson_id' => $lesson25->id,'user_id' => $user->id]);
$project15 = Project::create(['name' => ' Elapsed time','open_date' => '2018-07-14 0:00:00','close_date' => '2018-07-16 0:00:00','prompt' => '\n<div>In this project you find elapsed time. You will prompt the user to enter two times: a start time and a stop time, both in hours, minutes and seconds. You will then convert both to total seconds. Then subtract to find the elapsed number of seconds, then convert back to hours, minutes and seconds and display the result. Here"s an example:\n<pre><p>Enter start time hours: 1\n<p>Enter start time minutes: 30\n<p>Enter start time seconds: 19\n<p>Enter end time hours: 2\n<p>Enter end time minutes: 41\n<p>Enter end time seconds: 18\n<p>\n<p>The time elapsed between 01:30:19 and 02:41:18 is 01:10:59\n</div>\n','pre_code' => '','start_code' => '','solution' => 'h1 = 1#int(input("Enter time 1 hours:"))\nm1 = 30#int(input("Enter time 1 minutes:"))\ns1 = 19#int(input("Enter time 1 seconds:"))\nh2 = 2#int(input("Enter time 2 hours:"))\nm2 = 41#int(input("Enter time 2 minutes:"))\ns2 = 18#int(input("Enter time 2 seconds:"))\nt1 = h1*3600 + m1*60 + s1\nt2 = h2*3600 + m2*60 + s2\nt = t2 - t1\nh3 = t / 3600\nm3 = (t % 3600) / 60\ns3 = (t % 3600) % 60\nt1string = "{:0>2}:{:0>2}:{:0>2}".format(h1, m1, s1)\nt2string = "{:0>2}:{:0>2}:{:0>2}".format(h2, m2, s2)\nt3string = "{:0>2}:{:0>2}:{:0>2}".format(h3, m3, s3)\nprint("The time elapsed between {} and {} is {}".format(t1string, t2string, t3string))\n','module_id' => $module12->id,'previous_lesson_id' => $lesson25->id,'user_id' => $user->id]);
$project16 = Project::create(['name' => ' Random dot','open_date' => '2018-07-14 0:00:00','close_date' => '2018-07-16 0:00:00','prompt' => '\n<div>When the user presses spacebar, draw a dot or some other object flying into space. The dot should appear in some random location and fly in a random direction. Each time the user presses spacebar a new dot should appear and fly off. If a new dot appears, the old dot should disapper. You can use the turtle to be the dot or you can draw dots and clear each iteration. The starter code handles the pressing of the spacebar and will call shootDot() every time the spacebar is pressed.\n</div>\n','pre_code' => '','start_code' => 'import turtle\nimport random\nt = turtle.Turtle()\nt.penup()\nt.shape("circle")\nscreen = turtle.Screen()\ndef shootDot():\n    # TODO implement this function\nscreen.onkey(shootDot, "space")\nscreen.listen()\n','solution' => 'import turtle\nimport random\nt = turtle.Turtle()\nt.penup()\nt.shape("circle")\nscreen = turtle.Screen()\ndef shootDot():\n    dx = random.randint(-10, 10)/20.0\n    dy = random.randint(-10, 10)/20.0\n    x = 0\n    y = 0\n    t.setpos(x, y)\n    for i in range(1000):\n        x += dx\n        y += dy\n        t.setpos(x, y)\nscreen.onkey(shootDot, "space")\nscreen.listen()\n','module_id' => $module12->id,'previous_lesson_id' => $lesson25->id,'user_id' => $user->id]);
$project17 = Project::create(['name' => ' Throw physics simulation','open_date' => '2018-07-14 0:00:00','close_date' => '2018-07-16 0:00:00','prompt' => '\n<div>Write a physics simulation of a baseball being thrown from a cliff. A person throws a baseball horizontally with velocity v off a cliff. If there was no gravity the ball would travel straight. But since our dear planet has gravity, the ball starts to arc down toward the ground. You will ask the user how fast they want to throw the ball, and then show the parabolic arc traced out by the ball. See a solution in action <a href="https://youtu.be/leqa2zRqd-s" target="_blank">here</a>. (And yes, for you physics geeks out there, we are ignoring friction and all other forces besides gravity.)\n<p>See the two TODO comments for places to implement code.\n<p>To succeed in this project, you should take things in steps. For example, start by simulating a throw without gravity, and watch the turtle travel horizontally across the screen. Then add gravity. Print out values of variables if you get stuck. Take it slow!\n<p>One more tip: comment-out the code that prompts the user for a velocity while you"re writing your code. This way you can quickly test without having to enter in a velocity every time.\n</div>\n','pre_code' => '','start_code' => 'import turtle\nt = turtle.Turtle()\n# Returns the distance the ball will have fallen after time t\ndef fallingDistance(t):\n    return 0.5*9.8*t*t\n# Simulates throwing a ball from location (startx, starty) with\n# horizontal velocity v.\ndef throw(startx, starty, v):\n    y0 = starty\n    y = y0\n    x = startx\n    t.tracer(0)\n    t.up()\n    t.setpos(x, y0)\n    t.down()\n    t.tracer(1)\n    time = 0\n    # TODO Loop, incrementing x by the velocity each iteration.\n    # The y coordinate should be obtained using the fallingDistance\n    # function. Move the ball by calling t.setpos().\ndef main():\n    # TODO loop, asking the user what the desired velocity is,\n    # and calling throw() each time the user enters a non-zero\n    # value. Quit after the user enters zero. When calling throw(),\n    # the startx and starty location may be somewhere around\n    # (-180, 150), but this can be adjusted as desired.\nmain()\n','solution' => 'import turtle\nt = turtle.Turtle()\n# Returns the distance the ball will have fallen after time t\ndef fallingDistance(t):\n    return 0.5*9.8*t*t\n# Simulates throwing a ball from location (startx, starty) with\n# horizontal velocity v.\ndef throw(startx, starty, v):\n    y0 = starty\n    y = y0\n    x = startx\n    t.tracer(0)\n    t.up()\n    t.setpos(x, y0)\n    t.down()\n    t.tracer(1)\n    time = 0\n    # TODO Loop, incrementing x by the velocity each iteration.\n    # The y coordinate should be obtained using the fallingDistance\n    # function. Move the ball by calling t.setpos().\n    while y > -200:\n        time += 1\n        y = y0 - fallingDistance(time) / 10\n        x += v\n        t.setpos(x, y)\ndef main():\n    # TODO loop, asking the user what the desired velocity is,\n    # and calling throw() each time the user enters a non-zero\n    # value. Quit after the user enters zero. When calling throw(),\n    # the startx and starty location may be somewhere around\n    # (-180, 150), but this can be adjusted as desired.\n    v = int(input("Enter the velocity (0 to quit):"))\n    while v > 0:\n        throw(-180, 150, v)\n        v = int(input("Enter the velocity (0 to quit):"))\nmain()\n','module_id' => $module12->id,'previous_lesson_id' => $lesson25->id,'user_id' => $user->id]);
